{% extends 'extractors/_meta/extractor.j2' %}

{% block instructions %}
Identify the **topics** discussed in the source — broader subject
areas the source addresses. Aim for 5–12 topics; each should cover
a meaningful section or recurring theme.

For each topic:

- `name`: 2–6 words, capitalized as a heading would be.
- `relevance`: `primary` (a major subject of the source) or
  `secondary` (mentioned in service of a primary topic).
- `summary`: 2–4 sentences describing what the source says about
  this topic. Cite specific claims rather than abstract gestures.
- `source_quote`: a verbatim passage from the source that exemplifies
  the topic.

Topics are coarser than keywords — `state machines` is a keyword;
`software design` is a topic. Topics are also more abstract than
the primary `topic` (one classification-level descriptor); the
primary describes the source as a whole, while topics break it
down.
{% endblock %}

{% block builder_calls %}

    curator.sh builders add {{ task.output_path }} \
        --set topics.<i>.name='<2-6 word topic name>' \
        --set topics.<i>.relevance=primary|secondary \
        --set topics.<i>.summary='<2-4 sentences>' \
        --set topics.<i>.source_quote='<verbatim passage>'

All four fields are required for every topic.
{% endblock %}
